tionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webTitle":"Culture","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"film/film-industry","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webTitle":"Film industry","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/film-industry","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/film/film-industry","references":[]},{"id":"film/actionandadventure","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webTitle":"Action and adventure","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/actionandadventure","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/film/actionandadventure","references":[]},{"id":"film/animation","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webTitle":"Animation","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/animation","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/film/animation","references":[]},{"id":"film/kick-ass","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webTitle":"Kick-Ass","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/kick-ass","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/film/kick-ass","references":[]},{"id":"film/kick-ass-2","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webTitle":"Kick-Ass 2","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/kick-ass-2","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/film/kick-ass-2","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","type":"type","webTitle":"Article","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"profile/charles-gant","type":"contributor","webTitle":"Charles Gant","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/profile/charles-gant","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/profile/charles-gant","references":[],"firstName":"","lastName":"gant"}],"fields":{"headline":"Kick-Ass 2 leaps ahead, while Planes has smooth box-office take-off","standfirst":"The Matthew Vaughn and Brad Pitt-produced actioner packed less than the original, while Disney's animation soared nicely<br /><br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/series/at-the-british-box-office\">• Read the archive of Charles Gant's UK box office reports</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155968/kick-ass-2\">• More on Kick-Ass 2</a>","trailText":"<p>The Matthew Vaughn and Brad Pitt-produced actioner packed less than the original, while Disney's animation soared nicely</p>","byline":"Charles Gant","main":"","body":"<video data-media-id=\"gu-video-414933707\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/8/13/1376401925584/Chloe-Grace-Moretz-talks--016.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/8/13/130813KickAss2-16x9.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/8/13/130813KickAss2-720.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/8/13/130813KickAss2_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/8/13/130813KickAss2_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/8/13/130813KickAss2/130813KickAss2.m3u8\"/> </video>   <h2><strong>The winner</strong><br /></h2> <p>Thanks to Wednesday/Thursday previews totalling just over £1m, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155968/kick-ass-2\" title=\"\">Kick-Ass 2</a> lands at the top of the UK box-office chart with takings of £2.48m. It&apos;s the fifth chart-topper of 2013 for the distributor Universal, following <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/150107/miserables\" title=\"\">Les Misérables</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/133030/oblivion\" title=\"\">Oblivion</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155252\" title=\"\">Fast &amp; Furious 6</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/movie/155771/despicable-me-2\" title=\"\">Despicable Me 2</a>.</p> <p>While Universal and the production companies – Matthew Vaughn&apos;s Marv and Brad Pitt&apos;s Plan B – will be happy with the chart placing, closer consideration of the data yields less for them to celebrate. The original Kick-Ass debuted with £3.88m, including extensive previews of £2.05m, on its way to an £11.77m total. While you wouldn&apos;t always expect a sequel to match the total box-office of the original, you would certainly anticipate a relatively strong opening, since the film should inherit an engaged and motivated audience from its predecessor. Kick-Ass achieved a final total 6.4 times its three-day (Friday-to-Sunday) opening of £1.83m. It&apos;s a rare sequel that manages a multiple at that level.</p> <h2><strong>The real winner</strong></h2>      <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-415028884\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/8/14/1376496907157/John-Cleese-talking-about-001.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/8/14/130814Planes-16x9.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/8/14/130814Planes-720.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/8/14/130814Planes_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/8/14/130814Planes/130814Planes.m3u8\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/8/14/130814Planes_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"/> </video>   <p><br />Ignoring previews, the real winner at the weekend is the Disney animation <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156154/planes\" title=\"\">Planes</a>, with £1.74m. That&apos;s by no means among the top debuts for animations this year – well behind Despicable Me 2, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/151435/croods\" title=\"\">The Croods</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/150381/wreck-it-ralph\" title=\"\">Wreck-It Ralph</a>, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/movie/155588/monsters-university\" title=\"\">Monsters University</a> and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155263/epic\" title=\"\">Epic</a> – but perfectly fine for a little-heralded family pic that&apos;s arriving as a bonus offering at the fag end of the summer movie season.</p> <p>In this year&apos;s animation league table, Monsters University (£26.3m) is now just behind The Croods (£26.4m) and ahead of Wreck-It Ralph (£23.8m). Of course, all those titles are trailing far behind Despicable Me 2, which, with £42.7m, is the biggest UK box-office hit of 2013 so far. Monsters University opened with a lacklustre £3.46m, and has already achieved 7.6 times its debut. Among wide releases, that&apos;s likely to be one of the biggest multiples-of-debut for the year.</p> <h2><strong>The action hit</strong></h2>      <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-415205420\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/8/16/1376664899567/Denzel-Washington-and-Mar-015.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/8/16/130816Cutdown2Guns-16x9.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/8/16/130816Cutdown2Guns-720.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/8/16/130816Cutdown2Guns_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/8/16/130816Cutdown2Guns_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/640/2013/8/16/130816Cutdown2Guns_vpx.webm\"/> </video>   <p><br />With a solid £1.42m, the action thriller <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156151/2-guns\" title=\"\">2 Guns</a> manages a respectable third place, trading on the appeal of Mark Wahlberg and Denzel Washington in a zingy, spritely alternative to the summer&apos;s bloated CGI blockbusters. Wahlberg&apos;s last film, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/150235/broken-city\" title=\"\">Broken City</a>, debuted with a disappointing £499,000 back in March, its political-corruption storyline failing to connect with broader audiences. A more apt Wahlberg comparison is the heist flick <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/145687/contrabrand\" title=\"\">Contraband</a>, from 2 Guns director Baltasar Kormákur, which kicked off with £684,000 back in March 2012. That film lacked a co-star of equivalent weight to Washington, whose last actioner, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/146043/safe-house\" title=\"\">Safe House</a>, began its run in February 2012 with £2.14m. Awards-bait <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/149497/flight\" title=\"\">Flight</a> followed this February with a debut of £1.40m.</p> <h2><strong>The scrum</strong></h2>      <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-414638866\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/8/8/1375976616814/Composite-of-images-from--017.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/8/8/TGFS130809AlphaPapa-16x9.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/8/8/TGFS130809AlphaPapa/TGFS130809AlphaPapa.m3u8\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/8/8/TGFS130809AlphaPapa_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/8/8/TGFS130809AlphaPapa_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/8/8/TGFS130809AlphaPapa-720.mp4\"/> </video>   <p><br />Although not quite as clustered as the previous frame – which saw 11 films exceed £900,000 and none above £2.2m – the weekend again witnessed one of the least polarised box-office charts of recent years. The top title, Kick-Ass 2, grossed just 3.2 times the film in 10th place. Throughout July, despite no chart topper exceeding £5m, we witnessed multiples of the 10th-placed film as follows: x81; x45; x38; x60. Those numbers are much more typical of the kind of polarity experienced at the UK box-office – the exception being awards season, when the top film is more likely to gross around 10 times the 10th-placed film.</p> <p>At the weekend, seven films achieved sums in the £750,000 to £1m range, meaning that Disney&apos;s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156526/lone-ranger\" title=\"\">The Lone Ranger</a> finds itself out of the top 10 with £754,000, not so very far behind fifth-placed <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156145/the-conjuring\" title=\"\">The Conjuring</a> (£973,000) in cash terms. Cinema bookers will have a tough time accommodating all these releases that are faring averagely well, a challenge that becomes trickier with the arrival this week of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156639/mortal-instruments\" title=\"\">The Mortal Instruments: City of Bones</a> and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156629/elysium\" title=\"\">Elysium</a>. Expect more titles than ever to be scrunched into shared screens and reduced showtimes.</p> <h2><strong>The special event</strong></h2> <p>Not included in the weekend&apos;s figures for two very good reasons – live events are not tracked, and it occurred on a weekday – is <a href=\"http://www.vam.ac.uk/content/articles/d/david-bowie-is-happening-now-a-live-nationwide-cinema-event/\" title=\"\">David Bowie is Happening Now</a>, beamed live last week from London&apos;s Victoria &amp; Albert Museum. So-called alternative content is a flourishing sector in cinemas, especially for opera, ballet, theatre and classical music, and this summer we&apos;ve seen big numbers for Helen Mirren in the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/jun/19/audience-queen-helen-mirren-national-theatre-live\" title=\"\">National Theatre&apos;s The Audience</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/jul/17/kenneth-branagh-live-q-and-a\" title=\"\">Kenneth Branagh in the Manchester International Festival&apos;s Macbeth</a> and Dutch violinist <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/jan/09/pass-notes-andre-rieu\" title=\"\">André Rieu</a>. But live relays of a museum exhibition are a relatively novel phenomenon.</p> <p>Last Tuesday evening&apos;s Bowie event grossed £260,600 from 217 screens, says distributor Picturehouse, with sellouts in 42 venues. Encore screenings at 27 venues contributed a further £30,700, for a combined total of £291,300. The big four circuit chains – Odeon, Cineworld, Vue and Showcase – all participated, as did Picturehouse and independents. The result will inspire the big UK museums and galleries to explore the potential for their blockbuster shows, creating a live event capable of drawing a national cinema audience. David Bowie Is Happening Now was directed by Hamish Hamilton, who directed the live TV coverage for the Olympics&apos; opening and closing ceremonies, and included live testimony from the exhibition&apos;s curators and other experts.</p> <h2><strong>The future</strong></h2>      <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-415411314\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/8/20/1376986538031/Amanda-Seyfried-talks-abo-025.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/8/20/130820LoveLace-16x9.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/connectedTV/1280/2013/8/20/130820LoveLace-720.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/ad/2013/8/20/130820LoveLace/130820LoveLace.m3u8\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/8/20/130820LoveLace_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/8/20/130820LoveLace_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/640/2013/8/20/130820LoveLace_vpx.webm\"/> </video>   <p><br />With no film opening above £2.5m, overall the market is 15% down on the previous weekend and 22% down on the equivalent frame from 2012, when <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/146821/brave\" title=\"\">Brave</a> expanded into English cinemas and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/147726/bourne-legacy\" title=\"\">The Bourne Legacy</a> landed in second place.</p> <p>Cinema owners will be hoping for better from this week&apos;s new crop of films, which include the young adult fiction adaptation The Mortal Instruments: City of Bones, Neill Blomkamp&apos;s Matt Damon vehicle Elysium, the hit US comedy <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/video/2013/aug/15/were-the-millers-trailer-jennifer-aniston-video\" title=\"\">We&apos;re The Millers</a>, Jurassic Park 3D, and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156157/lovelace\" title=\"\">Lovelace</a>, starring Amanda Seyfried as the porn actress Linda Lovelace. Arthouse titles include <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/sep/12/what-maisie-knew-review\" title=\"\">What Maisie Knew</a>, updated from a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/henryjames\" title=\"\">Henry James</a> short story, and coming-of-age indie The Kings of Summer.</p> <h2><strong>Top 10 films</strong></h2> <p>1. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155968/kick-ass-2\" title=\"\">Kick-Ass 2</a>, £2,482,187 from 483 sites (new)</p> <p>2. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156154/planes\" title=\"\">Planes</a>, £1,735,940 from 508 sites (new)</p> <p>3. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156151/2-guns\" title=\"\">2 Guns</a>, £1,423,738 from 398 sites (new)</p> <p>4. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156134/grown-ups-2\" title=\"\">Grown Ups 2</a>, £1,119,025 from 367 sites. <strong>Total:</strong> £4,770,646</p> <p>5. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156145/the-conjuring\" title=\"\">The Conjuring</a>, £963,073 from 403 sites. <strong>Total:</strong> £8,121,962</p> <p>6. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155588/monsters-university\" title=\"\">Monsters University</a>, £892,945 from 491 sites. <strong>Total:</strong> £26,251,949</p> <p>7. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/151441/alan-partridge\" title=\"\">Alan Partridge: Alpha Papa</a>\\, £852,967 from 427 sites. <strong>Total:</strong> £4,201,795</p> <p>8. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156070/smurfs-2\" title=\"\">The Smurfs 2</a>, £836,599 from 516 sites. <strong>Total:</strong> £8,669,411</p> <p>9. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156147/percy-jackson\" title=\"\">Percy Jackson: Sea of Monsters</a>, £834,538 from 461 sites. <strong>Total:</strong> £4,264,614</p> <p>10. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155771/despicable-me-2\" title=\"\">Despicable Me 2</a>, £768,575 from 468 sites. <strong>Total:</strong> £42,676,372</p> <h2><strong>Other openers</strong></h2> <p><a href=\"http://www.movieplus.com/news/bollywood-box-office-news/once-upon-a-time-in-mumbaai-dobara-4-days-box-office-collection-below-expectations-59627/\" title=\"\">Once upon a Time in Mumbaai Dobara</a>, 45 sites, £106,573</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/145811/bachelorette\" title=\"\">Bachelorette</a>, 20 sites, £19,396</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155838/call-girl\" title=\"\">Call Girl</a>, 14 sites, £13,375</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156153/kuma\" title=\"\">Kuma</a>, six sites, £5,871</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156152/the-big-city\" title=\"\">The Big City (Mahanagar)</a>, three sites, £5,018 (rerelease)</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/156608/punjab-bolda\" title=\"\">Punjab Bolda</a>, nine sites, £3,116</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1780762/\" title=\"\">Aftershock</a>, three sites, £1,442</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/138022/when-the-dragon-swallowed-the-sun\" title=\"\">When the Dragon Swallowed the Sun</a>, four sites, £1,203</p> <p><em>Thanks to Rentrak</em></p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/series/at-the-british-box-office\">• Read the archive of Charles Gant&apos;s UK box office reports</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155968/kick-ass-2\">• More 